segments.text: I want to divide up this 30,000 into three instructor assistant professors and see what I can find.
I said we're beginning to be enough students in political science 206 and 7 which are the state required political science courses that we can and we've got some things to fill.
Well, so that was my first kind of policy decision.
He said, fine, break it up.
And I brought in a couple of instructors and an assistant professor.
And then I took a look at the curriculum.
Well, it had been designed from my predecessor asking the faculty, what would you like to teach?
Well, then we got a strange array.
For example, we had ancient political theory and no other.
There was not adequate work in politics, political parties, and so on.
So, we were pretty well off in comparative government, but nothing Latin American, and we're next to Mexico.
It seems to me perfectly obvious that there ought to be something that direction.
And so we undertake a full-scale curriculum revision.
Was anybody key to that?
Nobody special.
We as a faculty wanted committees and began to work it over.
Did they work together pretty well on that?
Yeah.
The third thing that I'd done almost immediately I sensed that my predecessor had been nasty Tibetan and he's what I call a bleeding-heart bureaucratic liberal.
I don't know whether you're familiar with the title, talk a wonderful human relations game and are arbitrary as hell when it comes to their own decisions.
So I told the faculty I'd like to do a deliberative faculty and I want to make it clear that
If we're discussing something, I want to hear all sides, and I don't care whether you differ with me or whether you don't.
I said, if we finally make a decision, I expect us all to do it.
But up to that point, I want everybody to feel free without fear and favor to express themselves.
Well, it took about six months before people began
talk and feel that maybe Van Riper meant what he said.
Now, during this period, you all were quartered physically where?
In the second story of the YMCA.
We had that floor, which had a couple of classrooms in it, enough offices.
My office is the one that was the personnel office for some time.
This man Benton, describe Gene Blue Book Benton.
Well, Gene was interesting in that he was the only one in the faculty that had any kind of reputation outside the university.
He'd done an excellent book on Nuremberg trials.
Gene was one of the worst lecturers possible.
But it was funny.
After a year or two, I would get letters back from people praising his legal training.
He did public law.
Because he said, Gene taught me to write a brief.
And as I say, as a lecture, he'd put you to sleep.
But I had the same problem at Cornell with Harold Gosnell, who was distinguished in the
The first man to do a political science book based on punch card voting.
This is 1930.
Eight or nine or so.
Progressive politics in Iowa.
And uses factor analysis and he does the whole goddamn thing by hand.
He was so far ahead of the game, but most of us, when he lectured, there are nuggets through this thing, but we figured half the time we wondered if he was drunk.
Did you ever, those of us who knew Benton heard him identified by the students as Blue Book Benton, were there any anecdotes that came to the department head?
No, not so much on that score.
Maybe I shouldn't say this, but I always heard him described as boobs-bent.
There's certain other attributes in the family.
But he and I always got along fine.
Now, he taught big sections in state government also.
He taught state and local government because he had a textbook in him.
And he was my saving when it came to schedules.
I always had to have some 8 o'clock courses, and Benedict wanted five right across the board.
Five 8 o'clocks was fine.
So I just laid those out, and that took care of my 8 o'clock.
Now, Jack Woods was nicknamed Jock Woods because supposedly athletes would pass his course always.
But Jack, I also got complaints about Jack
Because he taught, again, law work in administrative law and also, oh, I forget another course.
And Jack taught by the Socratic method, which God knows is peculiar enough undergraduate.
And some people would come in and say, I can't take it.
And I would let them out and not argue about it.
But more people, again, would write back, Jack taught me how the law worked.
So it was funny.
I had a lot of complaints on those two people, but the most compliment.
And Kwong Roe was already here?
Kwong Roe was here.
He was an associate professor with Denny.
What was his specialty?
His Far Eastern studies.
I kept trying to encourage Roe to do more publication because, and he finally did some.
But Kwong performed well as far as I was concerned.
Was there a master's degree when you got here?
Yes, they had just an ordinary MA.
About what was the enrollment in number of undergraduate majors and graduate majors?
Well, I'm trying to think of the figures then.
We had, I suppose, several hundred undergraduate majors.
Now it's two or three times that.
And of course we had enormous enrollments.
We had everybody in the university practically because Blinn College isn't here then much in American government and state and local government.
What about at the graduate level?
or five or six PhD candidates.
You mentioned, what about at the Masters?
How many Masters?
At the Masters, about, oh, it varied between, for two or three years, between five and ten.
Now, basically...
Tended to be more teachers who were... Could you generalize about the political science undergraduate majors, what their career goals were?
Well, it was very clear that we had a lot of pre-law, and we had a lot of core.
I was here one year, and the next year we were to have a self-study for crediting purposes.
And a professor from South Carolina came in and said, why are you teaching so much comparative government?
I said, we've got the core students are interested in it.
They're going to be all over the world.
I said, so we're a little disproportionate yet in terms of international affairs, comparative government.
Benton taught international relations as well as
So as I say, we wanted junior faculty.
We redid the curriculum.
I wanted a mixture of traditional and behavioral.
So to do justice to the behavioral, I set up the first departmental laboratory when we moved to Bolton Hall.
It had been the electrical engineering building, and it had all the connections.
So working with the head of sociology, we did a two-way mirror, and we didn't have computers then.
We had a bank of calculators.
And we set up a 208 and 9 as methodological courses.
I had gone through Chicago without a methodological course.
Nobody taught political science methodology.
I'd had some from White in the historical method.
I'd had Gosnell's work in political parties, but it was his quantitative work that was novel, but he didn't teach it as such.
I took a course in statistics and psychology.
And I took a course in accounting in the business school at Chicago.
So I had more than was customary in my generation.
It looked like this was coming, so I began.
And we've carried on ever since with the laboratory.
And so those are the main kind of thrusts at the beginning.
Then Maxwell asked for a five-year plan.
And I indicated something, building from the bottom.
We'd done the curriculum.
We had the laboratory.
I said, I would like to get an MPA and a PhD in due course.
I thought we ought to do the MPA first and then a PhD.
Did he seem fully supportive of these?
Oh, yes.
Yeah.
He just wanted us to have a plan.
He wasn't trying to tell us what it ought to be.
And so he also fully, he was one of the few deans who fully understood all, he was an economist, he understood the whole damn budgetary process.
In fact, he was working with the coordinating board in the legislature to get the per credit hour stuff modified to a certain amount of reality.
So then I developed a, to get us some additional income,
We could do an exemption exam for Poli Sci 206.
So I had done one at Cornell.
So I designed my own.
And we gave the exemption exam.
And we got the $15 per student who took it or passed it or not and added to our departmental funds to some extent.
And I needed maybe one less professor to teach a section.
Let's see, beyond that...
Describe the process of getting those two new degrees.
Oh, the... What was the red tape?
What were the hearings?
Well, the MPA was first.
I worked with the dean of business, John... Pearson.
Pearson.
On that, who had some interest.
He had a state and local finance man.
He had Arthur Wolfe, who was Ph.D. Chicago in personnel.
And so he had some things that would fit into a public program.
And he was supportive, thank heaven.
And so he and I designed one.
And unfortunately, the coordinating board, which had been passing everything, this is what led Gibb, my predecessor, to make a mistake on his PhD.
Coordinating board had been proving anything A&M asked.
Just as we got through the university faculty, our MPA proposal, courting board put a two-year moratorium on all new degrees.
So I'm... That doesn't do us any good for a Ph.D. either.
So I've been seven years a department head, and I decide that's enough, and we...
ride out the two years, and the MPA is then approved.
So that would have been about what year?
And we have a, it's going very nicely.
Heavily an evening effort, as it needs to be, although we had some courses in the regular time.
We must have had, after a year or two, we have 30 to 50 in residence at any one time.
So it began about the decade of 1980?
79, essentially.
Okay, 79.
And I'm the, I function as the director of it.
So you've done that now for?
I've done that for two years, and then retired.
Your history man became dean.
Oh, what's his name?
Following, he, who hated Nance.
Wait, wait, dean or president?
Dean, dean of liberal arts.
After Maxwell?
My mind is going blank.
Well, he was history all right.
Where'd he?
He'd been in the department, and I can't think of his name.
When we had all the former deans here, he came to dinner a while back.
Oh, I know perfectly well.
Well, we'll think of them in a minute.
Let's see.
Describe John C. Calhoun as vice president and Jack Kenny Williams as president during those years.
Well, the one I liked most was the generals.
He was president my first year.
Yes.
Describe working with him.
He didn't have much to work with.
He let us do what we wanted to do, but he's the only president who ever had the department head each one of them in for a visit.
Describe that visit.
It was very pleasant.
Asked me what I was interested in, where I came from, any special problems, and the rest of it.
Very calm and relaxed.
Did he seem like a good listener?
Yes, very much so.
Oh, yeah.
I had him into our pub ad program to lecture three or four times after that.
Describe him as a personality.
What was his style?
The calmest, most relaxed general I ever saw.
Did he seem well organized?
Oh, yes.
He knew exactly what he was doing.
I'm quite convinced.
And you can't be, you know, president.
Executive Vice President of TRW Systems and Director of the Atomic Energy Commission as well as a Major General without knowing what you're doing.
Yes, I thought he was a breath of fresh air and the most relaxed.
Things went right on without great
Horace Byers was academic vice president when I came.
This is the day when paperwork is still at a minimum.
He ran the academic vice president's office with, I think, an assistant and a secretary, and that was it.
One of the
Ag buildings.

So, yeah, the only real interesting thing I had with Horace Byer was I was wanting to offer a position to Elias Thermas in political theory and discovered that I had to get permission to him, that Elias did not have his final naturalization paper.
So I had to get permission to
are a foreigner.

So I wrote a semi-tongue-in-cheek note to Bayer that I'm requesting this because he's well qualified, he has a background, but also I think I'm hiring among other things to teach ancient political theory and I think it's highly appropriate that a Greek teach Plato and Aristotle.
Dr. Byers approved it immediately.
So, yeah, he was the only person, I think, in the whole blessed university faculty who was a member of the National Academy at that time.
Yeah, T-H-E-R-M-I-S. T-H-E-R-M-O-S, like Thermos Jug.
And then Dr. Byers retired.
And John Calhoun became the vice president, and Williams is by then president.
Describe your impression of them and working with them.
Calhoun had some of the problems of an engineer understanding the social sciences.
For example, I let my instructors teaching 206 and 207
choose their own textbooks.
Now, this was something Calhoun did not understand quite, because in the sciences, et cetera, you all agreed on a textbook.
Well, I got cold on that, and I said, look, all our textbooks operate one constitution.
They all revolve around it.
And I said, in Texas, we got one constitution also.
Now, this is our periodic table.
And I said, so I said, if you order me, I will comply.
But I said, they're getting substantially the same thing, but probably better because the people ordering textbooks are a little better able to teach it that way than some other way.
So I said, this doesn't bother me.
Then later on, we got some questions in the academic program committee, et cetera, about law.
Why shouldn't all law be one place?
Public law goes with business law.
I said, well, we have no particular use for business law.
They're well able to teach it.
I have nobody here to teach the common law or contracts or other things.
But I said, public law is constitutional law and administrative law, and the business people don't deal with that.
Now, I said, we're not playing in each other's bailiwick, essentially.
He finally understood that.
He and I are still on good terms, but I had to explain these things to a dean who wasn't quite so sure of what we were doing.
Well, I had one lecturer who was
accused of sexual assault on a student, of having sexual relations with a student.
I relieved him from teaching immediately.
He came in and gave me the story.
He said, yes, I had sexual relationship.
We had a wonderful evening.
She thoroughly enjoyed it.

I said I can well believe it but where do we go from here I said I'm relieving you until this is settled from your teaching and meanwhile attend to your courses and hope for the best well I got I figured this story is going to get to Calhoun immediately and because the

Carolyn Adair is in the Dean's office Dean of Students Office Dean of Students Office and she's all exercised over the girl so this gets to Calhoun and I figure I better be in early tomorrow morning because I'm going to get a call from Calhoun and I sure did about 8 15.
I was there to answer
I didn't always get in at 8 o'clock every morning.
And he said, what's the story?
And I gave him the story.
And he said, you mean without consulting me, you relieved a faculty member of his teaching?
I said, yes.
Said, what would you think if it came out that I had not relieved him in the press?
I had not relieved somebody so acute.
That kept him quiet.
What was his reaction to that response?
He said, OK, I guess you have a point.
I said, I'm on top of this, and we're handling it.
Well, sure enough, after the girl was afraid of her parents' reaction,
The girl would be candid afterward.
It had been consensual, completely so.
Did you have any, now your title was department head or chairman?
Head.
Head, all right.
And what did that mean to you compared to chairman?
Well, it was very clear what it meant.
push came to shove, I could do it.
And if you had your druthers today, would that be what A&M would do today?
Which is better?
I think in the long run chair is better because
Head gives people like my predecessor, Hornance, delusions of grandeur, very easy.
How long should the term be?
Well, I thought the period that I served my terms were in terms of five years.
And was there a review by some?
Yeah, Maxwell had a review, and I started the second.
term and two more years and I said I think this is I've done what I can do and the coordinating board's sitting on everything and somebody else can so we brought Sam Kirkpatrick in.
Who's done pretty well since then.
Yes I did think probably I said Dean if I'm resigning I said could I be chair to select of the committee to select my successor he said okay.
It's a little unusual how did y'all find Sam?
He came in by application.
He was at Oklahoma?
At Oklahoma, yes.
He had just been, I also knew him, he had just been president of the Southern Political Science Convention in his early 30s.
And he'd cleaned up a major scandal in that with very little.
There'd been a treasurer who'd been around for years who was taking advantage of the place.
And after being here, he went to Arizona State as dean.
And then president at UT San Antonio, now retired.
I don't know.
No, I think he still is.
Because he almost replaced me as president in 1987 at UT El Paso.

And I understand, that's my way of saying I don't, I'm not, I wouldn't stand up in court and say this is a fact, but I understand that it was a very close finish and that the board, the UT board kind of said, Dr. Kirkpatrick, just don't worry.
We'll have other vacancies and we'll get back to you.
And the next vacancy was at San Antonio and he was a good fit.
All right, looking back on those years in leading political science here, of what are you most proud of?
Oh, I think of just a collection of things, of getting things organized so the department had a quite firm base.
And when compared numerically, compare your first year and your last year in terms of majors and degrees.
Well, for example, when I came, we had 13 faculty equivalents.
My last year, we had a faculty of 40.
My, my.
My last year as department head, we hired 10 people.
It seemed to me I was visiting with faculty every day of the year.
And in terms of degree, the master's, the MPA was underway fully.
It had been designed and was before the coordinating board.
Let's see, we skipped over.
Did you have any relations with Dr. Williams?
And any comments about him and his leadership?
Not much, except I was in to visit him a couple of times.
